                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d13">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.5151/145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sevier</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-08T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 8, 1934—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. Your telegram No. 17, February 6, noon. The Department informally apprised
                    the Chilean Ambassador of the circumstances surrounding the Baldwin bid and
                    explained this Government’s viewpoint that its nationals should be given equal
                    treatment with other foreign competitors for Chilean business. It was made clear
                    to the Ambassador that all we ask is equality of treatment in the exchange
                    matter. The Ambassador said that he would cable his Government immediately,
                    urging that no step be taken which might be construed as discriminatory and that
                    American companies be given equal exchange treatment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
